        <font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"> Here is a little comparison about the 'old' pet and EoT</P><P><img src="http://home.arcor.de/neric/Xegony/EQ000319.JPG" border=0><BR>and that was just the 44 magnum!</P><P>original pet delay = 30<BR>Fine Steel dagger delay = 19<BR>Augment Dead = 55% haste<BR>Augmentation Dead = 65% haste</P><P>pet with original delay and augment dead = delay 19.35<BR>pet with FS dagger and augment dead = delay 12.26<BR>pet with original delay and augmentation dead = delay 18.18</P><P>EoT max damage = 71<BR>49 pet max damage = 55<BR>EoT = 23% more damage</P><P>pre-nerf pet delay with dagger and buff = 12.26<BR>EoT with buff = 18.18<BR>pre-nerf pet = 33% faster</P><P>49 pet was lvl 42 NPC fighting average NPCs of lvl 40<BR>EoT is lvl 46 NPC fighting average NPCs of lvl 46 (blue con)</P><P>EoT is hitting for max damage less often because most mobs con even or higher for it! So after all of this math...could it be that we pretty much have our pre-nerf-pre-Kunark pet back? </P><P>Hey, I am finally as strong as I was with lvl 50. Too bad that I am not fighting in Guk anymore and mobs are hitting 400% harder now with 400% more hps at least :(<BR>If I compare Ignite Blood (1200 DoT) with Funeral Pyre (2150 DoT), then my DoT is barely 100% better than in the old days. Of course not everything can be compared like that, but it pretty much shows that necros lost a bit of their power over the years....</P><P>Neric the Heretic<BR>~Darkwind~<BR>Antonius Bayle</P><P>Edit: Orignial numbers were wrong as Rekcim pointed out, so I corrected them, which makes the gap even more transparent.</P><P>Edited by - Neric Soulstalker on 08/25/2002  17:31:16</font></td>

